* New to the journey to Wuhan, he said, as long as can transport, he will be on the road

Retracing his journey to Wuhan, he said, he would be on his way as long as he could

This article was adapted from the Southern People's weekly

By Huang Jian

Editor | Jianping Zhou

When the New Year Bell Rang, Li Xing was driving a truck on the highway to Xiaogan City in Hubei Province. The road is hard to see car, occasionally met, and he is the same as the big truck.

It was dark all the way out the window, and there was only a little light as we passed some villages and towns. This time of year gorgeous fireworks, in this cold winter night, only sporadic bloom, let the lone on the highway Li Xing, finally feel a little New Year atmosphere.

There's a CCTV New Year's Gala on the radio. Unable to understand why, Li began to listen to a small video in Douyin: Some people were singing and laughing, spending New Year's Eve with their families; some were crying and grieving for their families'illnesses.

He clicked on his family's wechat voice, and his wife and children wished him "a happy new year, bon voyage, take care to protect yourself. "

Li Xing is a truck driver, originally intended to spend the New Year with his family, New Year's Day three or four or so back on the road, to continue his road career. A sudden outbreak of the disease changed his plans to spend New Year's Eve with his family.

A number of truck drivers have had their holiday plans changed by the epidemic this Spring Festival.

1
A sudden outbreak

"At the most difficult time, the government gave us help, gave us money for medical treatment and helped our children to go to school. In 1991, after the floods in Huainan, the local government helped rebuild the houses. Now the country is in trouble, and we have to give back. "

1
A sudden outbreak

1

###A sudden outbreak

"At the most difficult time, the government gave us help, gave us money for medical treatment and helped our children to go to school. In 1991, after the floods in Huainan, the local government helped rebuild the houses. Now the country is in trouble, and we have to give back. "

On January 21,2020, Li Xing was transporting the last of his cargo to Linyi, Shandong Province, with his son on board. The children seldom see him, clamoring to go out with their father after the holidays.

After the unloading, he could stay at home for a full week and spend the New Year with his wife and children. His family lives in Linyi, Linshu County, Shimen, Da Guanzhuang village. For many years he had been away from his family, sometimes on New Year's Eve.

Li Xing stayed at home for two days, the village more and more lively, red paper, lanterns, fireworks, noise, firecrackers... decorate the northern village. January 24 to the New Year's Eve, this lively but like a sudden illness, gradually become weak.

On the night of January 23, Li Xing's mobile phone was suddenly flooded with news about Wuhan. Wechat, Douyin, Toutiao... people are talking about the Wuhan epidemic on almost every online platform.

At 2:00 am on the morning of the 23rd, the headquarters for the prevention and control of COVID-19 pneumonia in Wuhan announced: from 10:00 am today, Wuhan bus, subway, ferry and long-distance passenger transport will be suspended; the airport and Railway Station will be temporarily closed from the Han corridor.

Wuhan traffic closure, Li Xingcai aware of the Hubei epidemic is very serious. He learned from the mobile phone that Hubei is short of medical supplies, some worry, sit. He got up the next morning, New Year's Eve, and had been filling the platform with orders to see if any had been shipped to Hubei from around Linyi. At noon, he saw an order, need to transport a batch of medical supplies to Xiaogan City, Hubei Province, immediately received orders.

He told his wife that he was not home for the New Year's Eve, to transport goods to the Hubei Epidemic area. His wife did not agree, I hope he can stay at home for the New Year, do not go anywhere, not to mention to the epidemic area, afraid he infected with the virus.

Li Xing insisted on leaving. "The epidemic is so serious, you said we do not have the money, we can moral support, to help themselves. If there is infected, special quarantine, all the consequences I have considered, I volunteer. "

He steeled himself and drove away with a friend from the same village, feeling a little guilty. "It's hard for me, too. I didn't spend the New Year with my family. "

On This Day, also on the road is truck driver Master Cao. Master Cao, who is over 50, is pulling a cart of medical supplies from Wenzhou to Wuhan. This time of year, he used to drive a sports car. Children are not at home, the home of the House has been sold, for him, at home and on the road, no difference.

His son is a soldier, is in Wuhan, advised him not to go to the epidemic area. But he was determined to go. As a young man, he made some money in business, gambled, got into a lot of debt, divorced his wife, and had two children of his own. "At the most difficult time, the government gave us help, gave us money for medical treatment and helped our children to go to school. In 1991, after the floods in Huainan, the local government helped rebuild the houses. Now the country is in trouble, and we have to give back. "

He began running to Wuhan on January 22, the same day he shipped a shipment of medical equipment to Wuhan. Over the next few days, he made six nonstop trips to Wuhan, carrying medical supplies to and from Hubei and Zhejiang provinces.

A few days later, Wang Hui, a driver from Tongling, Anhui Province, set off. On January 27, he was celebrating the New Year at home when he received a phone call from the company saying that some supplies needed to be shipped from Chuzhou, Anhui Province, to Wuhan. If he was willing to go, the company would give him a reward or a subsidy.

"The atmosphere is quite tense now. In my hometown, family and friends don't visit each other on New Year's Day. But I think I should go to Wuhan, not for reward, money is not as important as safety, " said Wang Hui, who drove to Chuzhou overnight on the 27th.

Li Xing

2
The van to the infected area

2

###The van to the infected area

Wuhan in the network world, as if in another world, make him unbearable to listen.

On the afternoon of the Lunar New Year, Li Xing had dinner, said goodbye to his family and drove to the delivery place in Linyi. A shipment of face masks, boots and masks was donated by a company to hospitals in Beijing and Xiaogan, Hubei Province.

Li wears a mask and disinfects his van with alcohol before the donor company loads it. It was 5:00 in the afternoon. The donor reminded him that the shipment was extremely urgent and had to be delivered by the end of the day. After eating fast food, Li Xing boarded the CAB and set off for the epidemic area.

A few hours later, he got off the highway in Zhengzhou and found a van waiting for him at the intersection. This is a car sent by the Beijing receiver to deliver Li Xingyun's protective mask and protective boots to Beijing. After handing over the goods, Li Xing continued on his way to Xiaogan, Hubei, carrying a mask.

The highway was empty, with occasional flashes of light, and cars heading north into the driveway. He drove at top speed and didn't have to worry about the usual traffic jams.

After 8 pm, the radio began to play CCTV New Year's Gala, finally a little bit of Spring Festival feeling. After listening for a while, he began to listen to videos played by friends in his village. Most of these videos were uploaded by Wuhan Netizens. The more he listened to them, the more excited he became. Wuhan in the network world, as if in another world, make him unbearable to listen.

His companion chatted with him for a while and gradually fell asleep. The road was silent except for the rumble of freight cars. The reflective signs on both sides of the road flitted silently through the night.

"there is no car in sight, no reference, no stimulation, it's easy to let down your guard, and when you see a car in front of you, you may not even have time to brake, " Li said after driving for more than nine hours and more than eight hundred and twenty kilometers without a break, on January 25, the first day of the Lunar New Year at 2:20 am, from Xiaogan Yangdian town under the highway.

After paying more than 400 yuan toll, traffic police and medical staff came from the toll station to take his temperature. Everything was normal. The road ahead is blocked. We can't go any further.

Five minutes later, volunteers from the hospital arrived. "I wore a mask in the car, and I didn't get close to them except to sign and open the door to unload for them, " said Li, who said he had been careful.

Wang Hui set out a few days after Li Xing. On January 28, he loaded up disinfectant at Jinhe Industrial Company in Chuzhou and drove to Wuhan. After the wee hours of the morning, flakes of snow began to fall on the windshield, the view getting worse and colder. He had to slow down. His car was the only thing moving in the quiet mountains.

After driving hundreds of kilometers through the blizzard, he arrived in the Xinzhou district of Wuhan at about 5 am on the 29th. Once at the Tollbooth, he was stopped by traffic police to check his temperature and identification. Then the receiving party, waiting near the toll booth, began to approach him to hand over the goods.

Like the other drivers, Wang Hui made a u-turn at the toll booth after handing over the supplies, leaving empty for Nanjing to deliver the next shipment to Wuhan. On the way, he received a call from a civil servant in his hometown. "He claimed to be some kind of secretary in Tongling and already knew that I had gone to Wuhan and asked me what I was doing there and how I was doing. "

3
En route

3

###En route

"I was on the road all the time, sleeping in my car and eating instant noodles. "

At 8 a.m. on Jan. 25, after unloading the cargo, Li turned around at a Xiaogan toll booth and drove back to his hometown in Linshu County. He wanted to take some goods back, earn a little road fare subsidies, but can not get off the highway, can not enter the city, there are orders can not be taken, not to mention almost can not find orders issued from the epidemic area, can only drive back empty.

He used to be on the road before and after the Spring Festival. Because many drivers go home for Chinese New Year, fewer people are carrying the goods, and the freight will be higher than usual. "At the end of the year, it can go up to about 2.6 yuan per kilometer, and during the Spring Festival, it can go up to 3 or 4 yuan, so I can earn some, " Li said. In the summer, the freight is especially low, averaging only about 2 yuan per kilometer.

"It costs a dollar a mile to burn gas, and with tolls, there is little money to be made. If it's a smaller van, it's a waste of time. From information to logistics, there's too much food in there and they have to earn some,"Li complained.

Li Xing, 34, has been a truck driver for 10 years. He is now a father of three, and his parents are in their 60s. He came out of school into the factory work, but the income is poor, then went to Hainan built two years dock, almost are "moonlight. ". He didn't think he had a way out, so he went back to his hometown, got his driver's license, and started driving people's vans.

Just after the Spring Festival in 2019, he took out a loan to buy a used Van and became a car owner himself. He had no money. He took out two bank loans totaling $110,000. "One is paying more than 2,000 yuan a month, and the other is paying interest first, which is more than 500 yuan a month, " said Li, who earns five hundred yuan a day to repay the loan and support his family.

For Li Xing, around the Spring Festival is the most profitable time of the year. But this Spring Festival, he can not make money. Though the highways are free to transport medical supplies to the affected areas, there is no freight on the return journey, and he does not earn much.

But at this particular time of the outbreak, Li is willing to accept that. "I drove almost 2,000 kilometers back and forth with no money, plus tolls and gas. I did my part. "

Li Xingkong car back, the toll station did not give him free passage, back to Linshu home, is already at night. He had a day off at home. On the afternoon of January 26, he took another delivery of disinfectant to Xiaogan, rushed to funing county in Jiangsu Province, and then rushed to Hubei overnight.

Li Xing drove in the snow for nine hours until 2.30 am on January 27th, when he handed over the disinfectant to a receiver who had come to pick it up at the toll booth in Xiaogan, before making another u-turn to his hometown of Linshu.

He drove all night through the snow to the plague-stricken area, returning exhausted and exhausted, stopping at a Xinyang highway service area, sleeping soundly before heading home again.

On the evening of January 28, he drove along the beijing-shanghai highway to the border of Linyi. He was about to get off at Honghuabu toll station in Tancheng County, but the toll station was already full of traffic police and medical personnel. Staff took his temperature, logged his ID and car information, knew he was coming from Hubei, told him to turn around.

"My temperature was over 36 degrees, but the traffic police in Tancheng County wouldn't let me off, so I had to get back on the highway. At the next toll station, the traffic police wouldn't let me off, and I ended up at the Luozhuang District toll station in Linyi before I got off the highway, " Li said. Little did he know that less than two days after leaving home, the situation had changed again.

Wang Hui was stopped by traffic police on an empty bus from Wuhan to Nanjing. The first time from Anhui into the territory of Jiangsu, the traffic police asked him to cooperate with medical staff to take temperature. The second time he got off the highway in Nanjing, he was stopped to take his temperature and register his information.

"I have a temperature of 36.5 degrees, but as long as I come from Wuhan, they won't let me off the highway, no matter whether my temperature is normal or not. I told them I wasn't from Wuhan. I did the right thing, but I can't go on record,"Wang Hui says of his experience.

After getting off the expressway from Nanjing, he took a rest in his branch office and drove to Zhejiang on the same day to load a batch of tables and chairs to support the Huoshenshan Hospital. As they were loading, the loader thought of shooting a little video from his cab and shuddered. Some stopped the loader from approaching the cab, saying it was coming from Wuhan. When Wang Hui saw this, "there was a subtle feeling in his heart, but nothing was said. "

When Master Cao was in Nanjing, he had a similar feeling. On January 25, he shipped 250 cases of face masks from Nanjing to Wuhan. During the loading, a worker said he had come from Wuhan to keep people away from him. He got into an argument with them because he thought the way they talked was too harsh. Fortunately, the situation did not escalate. When he arrived in Wuhan to hand over the goods, he found that a box of masks was missing. When he called the delivery company, he found that the workers who had quarreled had deliberately hidden the box of masks.

Since the outbreak, he has been traveling between Wuhan and various places. After delivery, want to go to a hotel to sleep at night, but were rejected, can only return to the car to sleep. Sometimes, get out of the car to ask for a pot of hot water noodles, will also be refused. Master Cao didn't like it.

However, there are also people who are enthusiastic. A few days ago, he was in a repair shop in Zhejiang tire, the boss learned that he shipped goods to Wuhan, invited him to eat at home. "during Chinese New Year, I was on the road all the time, sleeping on my car and eating instant noodles every day. " For the first time in about ten days, master Cao had a hot and serious meal.

4
14 Days in quarantine

4

###14 Days in quarantine

The village chief called to say that he had been to Hubei, just off the highway, let him not to return to the village.

At 8 p.m. on Jan. 28, as Li Xing got off the highway and drove down Yihe road toward his hometown of Caozhuang town, the village chief called to say that he had been to Hubei Province and had just gotten off the highway, telling him not to go back to the village.

When he heard the call, he was confused. "I didn't do anything. I just went to Hubei to deliver goods. I didn't get off the highway. How can I not go home? " He was a little hard to accept, but the village chief told him that it was the policy to go to the epidemic area and quarantine myself for 14 days, or stay at home, quarantine the whole family together, or go to a temporary quarantine point in the village.

"If really infected, quarantines at home that is not harm the family? " He chose to go to the village of temporary quarantine point. Shortly after 9 p.m. , he arrived at an isolation point on the Shuhe River, four or five miles from his village. All he could see was a prefabricated house, built on the Bank of the river. There was a bed and a table in the house, and his wife had prepared the bedding for him in advance.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The isolation room where Li Xing lives

The North Wind vibrates outside, and the house is as cold as an ICEHOUSE. He was angry that the village had not found a warmer place for him. "I would have been fine, but if I had a cold and a fever, what would they do if they came back to take my temperature? " He called the shipper to complain that he was transporting supplies to Hubei in order to support the people in the affected areas, but he could not return home, two weeks in a place like this.

He was unhappy with the conditions in the quarantine zone and worried that he would spend the next two weeks holed up in the hut, unable to work. "I have three children to support, a car loan to pay, a daily expenditure of at least 300 yuan, and a loan principal of 50,000 yuan by May. " Worried and worried, Li sent several messages to the full staff.

That night, Yunman promised to give him a daily allowance of 200 yuan during isolation. Still, he couldn't get over it, especially knowing that Gu Yaodong, the truck driver who had gone to Hubei with him, was finally quarantined in a better-equipped hotel. He took the coverlet from the van to the hut and wrapped himself up. The next morning, when he found out he didn't have a cold, he started to accept it.

On the same night, Gu Yaodong was in a similar situation to Li Xing. On the afternoon of January 28, Gu Yaodong and his wife, Tang Ziyue, returned from Wuhan after delivering disinfectant solution to the highway in Changzhou. Their home is in the west of Wuxi, near the exit of the Changzhou Expressway. A day ago, Gu Yaodong saw the online video about Wuhan, to deliver goods. Tang Ziyue is worried, want to share the risk with him.

Gu and his wife were asked by traffic police to get out of their car to take their temperature and register their information as they entered a toll station in Zouqu, Changzhou. Both have normal body temperature and no symptoms. After registering, the traffic police learned that they had come from Wuhan and asked them to go to an isolation point designated by the local government, or to return to the highway and go to the next toll station.

"The traffic police said that our information had been uploaded and would be tracked wherever we went, " Gu said, hoping to try his luck in Wuxi, turn the car around and get back on the highway. To the Wuxi Toll Station, under the high-speed cars have formed a long queue, traffic police and medical staff in the toll gate to queue information, temperature.

Gu Yaodong a little worried about going home, parked in the long line, line up. Staff sent him a "epidemic prevention and control notice, " issued by the Wuxi Epidemic Prevention and Control Emergency Command, which read:

"since January 26, any person who has travelled in Hubei Province for two weeks... must report to the site inspector and submit to the site inspector for a temperature check. If the patient does not have a fever, he or she will be placed in a centralized medical observation center or residence for a 14-day medical observation. If the patient has a fever, he or she will be transferred by 120 special buses to a designated medical institution for a fever outpatient clinic screening."

Nearly an hour later, it was Gu Yaodong's turn. After checking in, their temperature was normal. The traffic police told them to go to the observation post for 14 days. "We were the drivers who were transporting medical supplies to Wuhan, " Gu explained. "We unloaded the goods at the Highway junction. We didn't go into the city. We had to go back to the epidemic area to support them. " He hoped the traffic police would let him carry on with the shipments and that he would not be quarantined. The traffic policeman told him that they had "reported the situation to the authorities" and told him to wait in the car.

Ahead of him, several truck drivers who had been to Wuhan were quarantined. A few minutes later, a traffic cop came over and asked him if he could go home. "I can't go home, the village is closed. " Gu Yaodong explained that he lives in Wuxi. Traffic police said they would continue to reflect on his problems.

Gu Yaodong calls his father to ask him to take care of his one-year-old daughter. The couple slept in the car all night. In the past many nights, innumerable roadside, Gu Yaodong is such sleep in his car. The next morning, the traffic police came and told him that he had to be quarantined to enter Wuxi. Later, traffic police took them to a hotel near their home for observation.

Compared to the isolation board housing Li Xing lives in, Gu Yaodong couple in Wuxi treatment is much better. There's hot water, air conditioning, food's here, food's coming. "I asked about the food money, and the government said eat first and don't worry, " he told southern people weekly, a weekly newspaper. The isolated hotel is now full.

Delivery Platform let Gu Yaodong do not worry, will give him 200 yuan per day subsidy. He's come to terms with where he is. Each morning and afternoon, the medical staff came to take their temperature, but they couldn't go anywhere but hang out at the hotel with their phones, short videos and video chats with their children.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Ku yiu-tung

On January 31st Liu Cheng, the lorry driver, was also put under quarantine. But unlike Li Xing and Gu Yaodong, he is at home. The day before, he and his colleague Li Jie had delivered a truckload of disinfectant to Wuhan from 金湖, in east China's Jiangsu Province. After dropping Li Jie off at his hometown in Anhui Province, he drove home alone. He is a native of Guzhai village in Huaiyin District, Huai'an, and has been driving a van for two years since the 1990s.

He took his temperature at the East Huai'an Highway Toll Booth, checked his driving records, and when he got home, village officials and police and doctors showed up and took him to the Township Health Center for a CT and blood test. The results came back normal.

When he got home, the doctor carried a disinfectant sprayer on his back and sprayed every corner of his house. The police took pictures of him, told him not to leave the house, kept him in isolation for 14 days. Everyone in his house is in quarantine with him.

Every morning and afternoon, the police and the doctor would come to take his temperature and that of his family, and sometimes bring some necessities and food. Liu Cheng every day wearing a mask, nest in bed turned over the phone, to the meal point, the mother will bring in the food, except on the toilet, never leave the house.

He was comfortable with the situation. "The country has its own rules about staying home, " he said. The only thing that bothered him was the pungent odor of disinfectant.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li Jie and Liu arrived in a van at the Jinghe Toll Station in Wuhan to hand over the goods

5
Get back on the road

5

###Get back on the road

He said he didn't know how many more trips he could make, but as long as he could, he was on his way.

On February 11, Wang Hui drove to Wuhu, Anhui Province, to load a batch of appliances. He needed to be in Wuhan the next morning. Since leaving his home on January 27, he has been on the road for half a month, carrying five shipments of supplies to Wuhan. But starting around February 3rd, it got harder and harder for him to make deliveries.

With the development of the epidemic, Jiangsu, Zhejiang and other places have begun to restrict the use of goods vehicles to Wuhan under the highway. "I am a car from Anhui, and I can only get off in Anhui, " said Wang Hui, who said he and several of the company's drivers appeared to be fighting a guerrilla war. This time, after returning from Wuhan, he entered Anhui Province. He got off the highway near his hometown, Tongling, and changed the national highway to Wuhu to load goods. "If you come back from Wuhan and go directly to Wuhan, you can't get off the highway. "

In the current situation, like Wang Hui, Li Xing and others, such as voluntary travel to Hubei and other epidemic areas of truck drivers, is not the majority. "A lot of people have concerns and understand that going to Hubei, after all, is a risk of infection, " Wang Hui said.

Despite the growing difficulties of transportation, Wang Hui's boss, Guan Jiangnan, encouraged his men to try to ship supplies to Wuhan. "We have come up with a set of incentive plans. Drivers going to the affected areas during this period will receive a subsidy of 5,000 yuan for each trip within 500 kilometers, 10 yuan for each trip over 500 kilometers, and letters of commendation. "

Guan Jiangnan is the director of Anhui Huayan Logistics Co. , Ltd. . He introduced that the current epidemic areas are short of medical supplies, vegetables, grain and oil and other living materials, in addition to Hubei, Wenzhou and other places have also encountered similar difficulties. "Not many drivers are willing to go. Some drivers are willing to go, but they can't get out in their rural hometown. Now we have two drivers who don't want to go. They wanted to go before, but now they are afraid. "

Affected by the quarantine observation, as well as the restrictions on out-of-town vehicles in some places, Guan Jiangnan felt that the truck drivers were increasingly inadequate. His company usually cooperates with more than 600 trucks. During the Spring Festival, they counted only 80 or so trucks going out, and 15 trucks willing to go to Wuhan.

"Now our drivers deliver vegetables to some urban areas, and some local people won't let us in with out-of-town cars, " Guan said.

On the evening of February 11, after loading his cargo in Wuhu, Wang Hui resumed his journey to Wuhan in his van. He said he didn't know how many more trips he could make, but as long as he could, he was on his way.

(correspondents Nie Yangxin, Mei Han, Du Lihua and Xiong Fangping contributed reporting.)
